  Notable (Test/Infra Code)

  - Multiple TLS_ECDHE_RSA_* and TLS_RSA_WITH_* cipher suites in test infrastructure — not production risk but reflect assumptions about acceptable algorithms
  - wso2-synapse/modules/core/.../PqcHttpsServer.java — a proof-of-concept already exists using ML-KEM (Kyber), Falcon, Dilithium via Bouncy Castle's PQC provider. This is not wired into
  production

  ---
  Prioritized Recommendations

  Quick wins (low effort, clear benefit):
  - PatchUtils.java: MD5 → SHA-256. No behavior change, just stronger integrity check
  - WSSecSignature.java: Change default digest from xmldsig#sha1 → xmldsig#sha256
  - SystemUserRoleManager.java: SHA1PRNG → new SecureRandom() (Java will select best available)

  Medium-term:
  - KeyStoreUtil.java: RSA/ECB/OAEPWithSHA-1AndMGF1Padding → RSA/ECB/OAEPWithSHA-256AndMGF1Padding — same RSA, stronger hash
  - JWTAuthorizationProvider.java: remove SHA-1 thumbprint fallback
  - WSConstants.java: change RSA default to RSA_SHA256 or RSA_SHA512

  Long-term (needs design work):
  - CryptoUtil.java RSA encryption — migrate to hybrid encryption (RSA-KEM + AES-256 or ML-KEM once standardized)
  - Transaction encryption — same as above
  - TLS: enforce TLS 1.3 + disable TLS_RSA_WITH_* cipher suites; prefer TLS_AES_256_GCM_SHA384

  The PqcHttpsServer.java POC is already using the right libraries (BC PQC). The long-term path is wiring ML-KEM / ML-DSA (NIST FIPS 203/204) through the existing BC provider infrastructure
   you've already set up.